We do not handle evacuations orders. Please contact your local Emergency Management agency for that information.

The current forecast shows a landfall near PCB/Mexico Beach tomorrow afternoon. However, hurricanes are not just points on a map. Winds will continue to increase through the night near the coast, with the strongest winds expected Wednesday.

We do not have information regarding road closures. You should contact your local police department or local emergency manager officials. Nevertheless, keep in mind winds will begin to quickly pick up early tomorrow morning.

Although the storm should begin weakening just after landfall, winds will continue to produce life threatening conditions well inland. This includes Tallahassee and nearby areas. There is also a threat for isolated flash flooding and a few tornadoes.

The official forecast has a category 3 hurricane making landfall near PCB/Mexico beach. However, a category 4 landfall cannot be ruled out at this point. Please refer to the latest @ NHC_Atlantic updates on Michael. The next one will be at 11 pm.

Deterministic point forecasts like these are not representative of an entire area. All interest groups around PCB should be prepared for major hurricane impacts. This includes life-threatening storm surge, damaging winds, and isolated flash flooding.

If you are referring to landfall timing, we expect it to be Wednesday afternoon/evening around the Panama City Beach/Mexico Beach area. However, tropical storm force winds can begin as early as late tonight for our coastal areas and will only increase through Wednesday.

Landfall is expected a few miles east of Panama City Beach. However, it is important to remember that hurricanes are not a just a point on a map and their effects are widespread. Folk should be ready for tropical storm and hurricane impacts along the entire FL Panhandle.
